The supposed mineral wealth of Britain attracted the cupidity of the Romans. Tacitus, like Strabo, talks of its possessing gold, silver, and other metals, which made it worth while to conquerit. Caesar himself (v. ra, 5 4) appears to mention gold coins as being in use in Britain. The reading, it is true, is very doubtful, but it is supported hythe views of numismatists, who hold that gold coins vere struck in Britain about a century before Caesar's landing. However that may be, Caesar himself got no gold out of the country.
